# Full Analysis: 


TVAAS stands for Tennessee Value-Added Assessment System.


It was developed by William Sanders and colleagues at the University of Tennessee in the late 1980s and became operational statewide in Tennessee in 1992. It was the first large-scale operational VAM system in the US and is what put value-added modeling on the map for education policy.
A few things made it notable:



Substantively — Sanders used it to argue that teachers were the single most important school-level factor in student achievement, and that the effects of having a highly effective vs. ineffective teacher were large and cumulative. That finding drove enormous interest from policymakers.


Methodologically — the layered model was his solution to the cross-classification problem. Rather than the simpler gain score or covariate adjustment approaches that were common at the time, he built a model that kept all prior teachers in the equation simultaneously. That was genuinely innovative for the early 1990s.


Politically — Tennessee's adoption of TVAAS for teacher evaluation made it one of the most controversial systems in education policy. It was later adopted or adapted by other states and became central to federal Race to the Top funding debates around 2009-2012, where states were incentivized to use student test scores in teacher evaluations.
The McCaffrey et al. paper you're working from is essentially a formal statistical examination of whether Sanders' model actually does what he claimed — and whether its assumptions hold up. That's why the General Model's ability to estimate α\alpha
α rather than assuming it equals 1 is such a direct challenge to the core TVAAS assumption.



